\uc0\u8232 \
\uc0\u8232 \
#Two \
\uc0\u8232 Under heaven all can see beauty as beauty only because there is ugliness. \u8232 All can know good as good only because there is evil. \u8232 Therefore having and not having arise together. \u8232 Difficult and easy complement each other. \u8232 Long and short contrast each other: \u8232 High and low rest upon each other; \u8232 Voice and sound harmonize each other; \u8232 Front and back follow one another.\
Therefore the sage goes about doing nothing, teaching no-talking. \uc0\u8232 The ten thousand things rise and fall without cease, \u8232 Creating, yet not possessing.\u8232 Working, yet not taking credit. \u8232 Work is done, then forgotten. \u8232 Therefore it lasts forever.\
\'a0\
\uc0\u8232 \
\uc0\u8232 \
#Three \
\uc0\u8232 Not exalting the gifted prevents quarreling. \u8232 Not collecting treasures prevents stealing. \u8232 Not seeing desirable things prevents confusion of the heart. \u8232 The wise therefore rule by emptying hearts and stuffing bellies, by weakening ambitions and strengthening bones. \u8232 If men lack knowledge and desire, then clever people will not try to interfere. \u8232 If nothing is done, then all will be well.\
\'a0\
\uc0\u8232 \
\uc0\u8232 \
#Four\
 \uc0\u8232 The Tao is an empty vessel; it is used, but never filled. \u8232 Oh, unfathomable source of ten thousand things! \u8232 Blunt the sharpness, \u8232 Untangle the knot, \u8232 Soften the glare, \u8232 Merge with dust. \u8232 Oh, hidden deep but ever present! \u8232 I do not know from whence it comes. \u8232 It is the forefather of the gods.\
\'a0\
\uc0\u8232 \
\uc0\u8232 \
